    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-04-14T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-04-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="388"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d388">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">891.00/1857</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Adviser on Political Relations</hi>
                        (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Murray</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Under Secretary of State</hi> (<persName
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Welles</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-04-14">April 14,
                            1942</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Welles</hi>: I think that we may assume from the
                    attached telegrams from Tehran<note n="94" xml:id="d388fn94">Telegrams No. 103,
                        April 12, 10 a.m., <ref target="#pg_332">p. 332</ref> and No. 104, April 13,
                        noon, <hi rend="italic">supra</hi>.</note> that our objective in Iran was
                    accomplished and relations with Japan were severed without the necessity of
                    delivering our rather stiff note of April 10.<note n="95" xml:id="d388fn95">See
                        telegram No. 85, April 10, 2 p.m., to the Minister in Iran, <ref
                            target="#pg_330">p. 330</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>This is, I believe, all to the good, since the Iranian Minister is already
                    pressing us to “reward” his Government for its behavior in this matter.</p>
                <p>Upon the Minister’s return to Washington from New York, where he expects to spend
                    about a week, I intend to follow the suggestion contained in the memorandum of
                    your conversation with the Minister last Saturday,<note n="96" xml:id="d388fn96"
                        >April 11.</note> and to discuss with him the precise measures we
                    contemplate taking with a view to assisting Iran in her present difficult
                    situation.</p>
                <p>I sensed from a brief conversation I had with the Minister, following his
                    conference with you, that he expects large Lend-Lease benefits to start to flow
                    at an early moment as a result of his Government’s acquiescence in our demand
                    that relations with Japan be severed. I shall, of course, have to make it clear
                    to the Minister that Lend-Lease status for Iran does not mean that the Iranian
                    Government will necessarily be furnished with all it may ask for; that, on the
                    other hand, we are already rendering great assistance to Iran by facilitating
                    the purchase in this country of sorely needed commodities; that we are
                    endeavoring to find for them a competent officer to <pb facs="0346" n="334"
                        xml:id="pg_334"/> reorganize the police and security forces of the country
                    and two agricultural experts to assist in fighting pests and diseases which are
                    attacking their crops; that we are exploring with the War Department the
                    possibility of finding an able officer to act as Quartermaster General for the
                    Iranian Army; and that, if they so desire, we shall be prepared to assist them
                    in finding advisers for finance and food distribution. I shall also mention the
                    trade agreement negotiations<note n="97" xml:id="d388fn97">For correspondence on
                        this subject, see <ref target="#pg_276">pp. 276</ref> ff.</note> which are
                    now in progress.</p>
                <p>This certainly is no inconsiderable list of benefits that Iran will enjoy by
                    taking an action which not only satisfies us but which removes a really great
                    danger to herself.<note n="98" xml:id="d388fn98">Marginal note by Mr. Welles: “I
                        fully agree.”</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wallace Murray</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
